🔒 SECURITY VULNERABILITY ANALYSIS - ownCloud Core API

Based on my analysis of the OpenAPI schema, covered files, and endpoint definitions, here are the critical security issues identified:
🚨 CRITICAL SECURITY CONCERNS
1. Authentication Weaknesses

    Multiple inconsistent auth schemes: OCSAuth, BearerAuth, OCSAPIKeyAuth, ADMIN_AUTH, SUBADMIN_AUTH, USER_AUTH
        Risk of privilege escalation if token handling varies between endpoints
    Missing CSRF protection on 45+ sensitive endpoints:
        Federated sharing operations (/ocs/v2.php/apps/federatedfilesharing/*)
        Password reset flows (/lostpassword/*)
        System updates (/core/ajax/update.php)
        User/group management endpoints

2. Authorization Gaps

    User/Group Management: Relies on bearer tokens without scope verification
        /cloud/users, /cloud/groups endpoints accept ADMIN_AUTH/SUBADMIN_AUTH but lack granular control
    Federation Trust: No detailed authorization for trusted server establishment
        Risk of unauthorized trust relationships being created
    Private Data Access: /privatedata/* endpoints have minimal protection

3. Data Exposure Risks

    User Enumeration via Avatars: /avatar/{userId}/{size} allows fingerprinting user IDs
    Sensitive Metadata Leakage:
        Share listings reveal file paths, permissions, and ownership details
        User entities expose email addresses, storage quotas, group memberships
        Response schemas contain internal status codes that aid reconnaissance

4. Input Validation Issues

    Password Reset Token Security: No validation requirements specified for reset tokens
    Share Permission Bitmask: Accepts values 0-31 without clear constraints or validation
    Federation Server URLs: No format validation for remoteServer field in trusted server configuration

5. Federation/Trust Management Vulnerabilities

    Trusted Server Endpoints: /ocs/v2.php/apps/federation/trusted-servers allows adding/removing trust without sufficient controls
    Shared Secret Exposure:
        GET endpoint exposes sensitive federation authentication tokens
        POST endpoint for requesting secrets lacks rate limiting
    Auto-add Servers Feature: Could be exploited to establish unauthorized connections

6. Password Handling Weaknesses

    Complex Recovery Flow: Multiple endpoints (/lostpassword/email, /reset/form/{token}/{userId}, /set/{token}/{userId}) increase attack surface
    Historical Vulnerability: Changelog mentions incorrectly sent password reset tokens (issue #32889)
    Token Security Not Specified: No validation requirements in OpenAPI schema

7. Error Message Disclosure

    Information Leakage: OCSResponse schemas reveal internal status codes and system state through failure messages
        Examples: "Share not found", "Invalid credentials or token expired"
    Generic Responses: Could aid attackers in understanding system behavior

8. Rate Limiting Absence

    No Built-in Protection: No rate limiting documented for:
        Authentication endpoints (/api/v1/login/)
        Password reset operations (/lostpassword/*)
        Token generation (/api/v1/token/generate/)
    Reliance on External App: Brute force protection exists as separate app, indicating gaps in core API security

📋 OWASP API SECURITY TOP 10 MAPPING
OWASP Category 	Finding 	Severity
API1: Broken Object Level Authorization 	Direct object access via IDs (share_id, user_id, group_id) without proper authorization checks 	🔴 Critical
API2: Broken Authentication 	Multiple inconsistent auth schemes with potential token handling gaps 	🟠 High
API4: Insecure Inventory 	Comprehensive endpoint documentation aids attackers (70+ endpoints exposed) 	🟡 Medium
API5: Broken Function Level Authorization 	Broad ADMIN_AUTH/SUBADMIN_AUTH roles without granular controls 	🔴 Critical
✅ RECOMMENDATIONS FOR REMEDIATION
Immediate Actions:

    Implement Consistent CSRF Protection across all state-changing operations (POST/PUT/DELETE)
    Add Rate Limiting to authentication, password reset, and token generation endpoints
    Strengthen Input Validation for federation server URLs and share paths with strict format requirements
    Reduce Error Information Disclosure - use generic error messages without system details

Short-term Improvements:

    Implement Scope Verification for all token-based authentication (OAuth2-style scope validation)
    Add Granular Authorization at API gateway level with explicit permission checks per endpoint
    Secure Federation Trust Management with multi-step approval and audit logging
    Password Reset Security Enhancement - implement token rotation, expiration, and usage limits

Long-term Architecture:

    Standardize Authentication Framework - migrate to OAuth2/OIDC for consistent security model
    Implement API Security Gateway with built-in rate limiting, validation, and threat detection
    Comprehensive Audit Logging for all sensitive operations (user management, federation changes)

📊 RISK ASSESSMENT SUMMARY

    Critical Issues: 4 (Object-level authorization, broken function auth, CSRF gaps, federation trust)
    High Risk: 3 (Authentication inconsistency, password handling, data exposure)
    Medium Risk: 2 (Error disclosure, rate limiting absence)
    Overall Security Posture: ⚠️ Moderate-High Risk - Requires immediate attention to critical findings

All detailed findings and recommendations have been documented in memory under owncloud_api_security_vulnerabilities for future reference and remediation tracking.